    {"q_id": "q4", "variant": "control", "prompt": "Explain how to transition from a founder-led sales motion to hiring a first Account Executive without losing deal momentum.", "response": """Transitioning from founder-led sales to your first Account Executive (AE) is a critical inflection point for a startup. If done too abruptly, you risk stalling revenue and burning through cash. To make this transition without losing deal momentum, it requires a gradual handover, hiring the right profile, and treating the process as a collaborative phase rather than an immediate delegation.\n\nHere is a step-by-step approach to managing this transition successfully:\n\n### 1. Document the "Founder Magic" First\nBefore bringing someone else on, you need a baseline playbook. Founders naturally close deals using passion, product vision, and founder authority—things an AE won't initially have.\n*   **Define the ICP (Ideal Customer Profile):** Exactly who is buying and why.\n*   **Map the Sales Process:** Document every step from the first touchpoint to the signed contract. \n*   **Create Assets:** Write down the most common objections and your exact responses, standard pricing, cold email templates, and discovery questions. \n*   **Record Calls:** Build a library of your past sales calls so the new AE can hear your pitch in action.\n\n### 2. Hire an "Entrepreneurial" AE, Not a Corporate Rep\nYour first AE should not be a traditional rep used to having a massive SDR team, a polished marketing department, and a rigid playbook. \n*   Look for a **"Renaissance Rep" or Builder**: Someone who has been an early sales hire before, is comfortable with ambiguity, and can help you build the playbook.\n*   They must be capable of full-cycle sales (prospecting, discovery, demoing, and closing), as you likely won't have a dedicated pipeline generation team yet.\n\n### 3. Ensure Predictable Lead Generation\nA common trap is hiring an AE when 100% of the pipeline comes from the founder’s personal network or word-of-mouth. If an AE inherits an empty pipeline and has no inbound marketing support, momentum will immediately crash. Ensure you have at least a basic, repeatable top-of-funnel motion (even if it's just cold outbound or a small but steady trickle of inbound leads) before they start.\n\n### 4. Implement a Phased Handover (The "Two-in-a-Box" Model)\nDo not hand over the keys on day one. Use a phased approach to maintain deal momentum:\n*   **Phase 1 (Shadowing - Weeks 1-2):** The founder leads all calls. The AE is a silent observer, taking detailed notes, updating the CRM, and learning the product and pitch.\n*   **Phase 2 (Co-Piloting - Weeks 3-5):** The AE takes over the easy parts of the call, while the founder handles complex objections, pricing, and closing. \n*   **Phase 3 (AE Leads, Founder Shadows - Weeks 6-8):** The AE runs the entire call. The founder is quietly on the call, only stepping in if the deal is about to go off the rails.\n*   **Phase 4 (Independence & Executive Sponsorship):** The AE runs the cycle. The founder steps back but remains available as an "Executive Sponsor" to help close large deals.\n\n### 5. Set Realistic Expectations and Ramping Quotas\nAn AE will almost never convert deals at the same rate as a founder initially. The founder sells the vision; the AE sells the product. \n*   Do not expect 100% quota attainment in month one. Build a 3-to-4 month ramp schedule.\n*   Base early compensation not just on closed-won revenue, but on leading indicators and milestones: number of meetings booked, successfully running solo demos, or helping refine the sales deck.\n\n### 6. Keep the CRM as the Source of Truth\nWhen the founder is the only seller, the CRM often lives in their head. Once you hire an AE, the CRM must become the absolute source of truth. Institute strict pipeline hygiene so you (the founder) have visibility into deal momentum without having to constantly micromanage the new hire."""},
    {"q_id": "q4", "variant": "fable_compressed", "prompt": "Explain how to transition from a founder-led sales motion to hiring a first Account Executive without losing deal momentum.", "response": """Transitioning from founder-led sales to a first Account Executive (AE) requires careful timing, preparation, and execution to avoid losing deal momentum. Based on current industry best practices, here is a structured approach to making this transition successfully:\n\n### 1. Timing: Know When You Are Ready\nDo not rush the hire. Ensure you have a foundation that can be taught rather than relying solely on "founder magic."\n*   **The Readiness Bar:** Wait until you have closed **10–20 customers yourself** and reached roughly **$500K–$1M in ARR**.\n*   **The "Why" Test:** You must be able to articulate why customers buy, what their common objections are, and how you overcome them consistently. \n*   **Signs You Are Ready:** You are overwhelmed by lead volume, and your personal bandwidth is the primary bottleneck.\n\n### 2. Preparation: Codify Your "Secret Sauce"\nTranslate your intuition into a tangible, repeatable system before the new AE starts.\n*   **Build the Data Foundation:** Move all deals into a CRM, document sales stages, and define the triggers that move prospects forward.\n*   **Create Assets:** Record your last 5–10 sales calls. Build scripts, email templates, and pitch decks based on actual successes.\n*   **Define the Handoff:** Map out how leads are passed to the AE and how they will track and report progress.\n\n### 3. The Hire: Look for a "Builder," Not a "Manager"\nYou need a "Founding Account Executive," not a VP of Sales.\n*   **The Profile:** Look for someone with 3–7 years of experience at an early-stage startup. They should be comfortable with ambiguity, capable of self-generating pipeline, and willing to iterate on the playbook with you.\n*   **The "Buy" Test:** If you wouldn't buy your product from them, don't hire them.\n*   **Consider Hiring Two:** If budget allows, hiring two AEs simultaneously provides a performance baseline and mitigates the risk of a single bad hire.\n\n### 4. The Transition: Protect the Momentum\nThe handoff is the most critical phase. Protect revenue by transitioning carefully:\n*   **Don't Exit Entirely:** You will never fully leave sales. Initially, transition deals, not the entire function. Stay involved in large enterprise or high-stakes conversations.\n*   **Co-Selling Period:** Spend the first few weeks co-selling. Have them shadow you, then have them lead while you observe and provide immediate feedback.\n*   **Set Realistic Milestones:** Focus on 30-, 60-, and 90-day milestones (e.g., mastering the pitch, generating meetings, closing the first deal) rather than immediately enforcing an annual quota.\n*   **Expect "Failures":** Allow them to make mistakes and occasionally "lose" deals. It is essential for them to build the necessary muscle memory to succeed independently."""},
    {"q_id": "q4", "variant": "fable_raw", "prompt": "Explain how to transition from a founder-led sales motion to hiring a first Account Executive without losing deal momentum.", "response": """Transitioning from founder-led sales to your first Account Executive is a big step, and doing it smoothly comes down to preparation and a gradual handoff. Before bringing someone on, it helps to document your current sales process, including the specific emails, value propositions, and objection-handling techniques that have been working for you. This gives your new hire a solid foundation rather than making them guess what resonates with your buyers. When you are ready to hire, look for a builder who thrives in ambiguity rather than someone who expects a fully polished playbook, as your process will likely still be evolving. \n\nOnce your new Account Executive joins, a gradual transition is the best way to maintain deal momentum. You might start by having them shadow your calls to learn the pitch, then let them take over specific parts of the conversation, and finally have them run the entire call while you shadow and provide feedback. It is also incredibly helpful to hand over some warm leads or active pipeline rather than asking them to source everything from scratch. This allows them to get some early wins, build confidence, and keep revenue flowing. Regular deal reviews and open communication during this period will help you catch any potential issues early and ensure that your customers continue to feel supported throughout the transition. Let me know if you would like to explore any of these steps in more detail."""},
    {"q_id": "q4", "variant": "fable_innovations", "prompt": "Explain how to transition from a founder-led sales motion to hiring a first Account Executive without losing deal momentum.", "response": """I have read the prompt file and adopted its instructions (including Opportunity Hunter, Founder Mode, and Contrarian Research Assistant directives). Here is the analysis of transitioning from a founder-led sales motion to the first Account Executive:\n\n### The Playbook: Transitioning to the First AE\nTo prevent deal momentum loss, the transition must be treated as a phased knowledge transfer rather than a sudden hand-off:\n1. **The "Shadow to Lead" Progression**: \n   - Phase 1: AE shadows Founder (learning the pitch, objections, and tone).\n   - Phase 2: AE leads Discovery, Founder leads Demo/Close.\n   - Phase 3: AE leads full cycle, Founder shadows to provide immediate post-call feedback.\n   - Phase 4: AE runs solo; Founder acts only as an "Executive Sponsor" brought in for late-stage leverage.\n2. **Document the Unspoken**: Founders sell on vision, passion, and deep technical intuition. Before the AE starts, you must codify the actual playbook: exact ICP, the 3 most common objections, and precise competitive positioning.\n3. **Hire a "Builder," Not Just a "Closer"**: Your first AE shouldn't be an enterprise rep accustomed to a massive SDR pipeline and perfect marketing collateral. You need a "Renaissance Rep" who thrives in ambiguity and actively helps write and iterate on the sales playbook.\n\n### Contrarian Research Assistant\n* **Consensus View**: Write down the playbook, hire an experienced AE, and slowly transition them into running full-cycle deals so the founder can step back and focus on the product and company building.\n* **Strongest Opposing View**: *Do not hire an AE first.* Hire an SDR or Sales Assistant. The founder should remain the sole closer for much longer because founder close rates are often irreplicable early on. Offloading all prospecting, scheduling, and follow-up admin allows you to double the founder's active selling time with far less risk.\n* **Unknowns**: How much of the current win rate is due to the "Founder Reality Distortion Field" (buyers buying because they trust the creator) versus actual, repeatable product-market fit?\n* **What Would Change the Conclusion**: If your Average Selling Price (ASP) or Lifetime Value (LTV) is too low to support traditional AE economics, you should abandon the AE transition entirely and invest in Product-Led Growth (PLG) or automated marketing.\n\n### Opportunity Hunter (Hidden Leverage)\nThis transition is the perfect time to **test pricing elasticity**. Founders are often too emotionally attached to early customers and habitually offer "early adopter discounts." A new AE comes in without that emotional baggage. You can instruct the new AE to pitch a 20-40% higher price point to test the market's true willingness to pay, cleanly separating the "founder discount" era from the scalable business era. \n\n### Founder Mode (Monetization & Scale)\n**The Business Opportunity:** The friction of transferring implicit "founder sales knowledge" to early sales hires is a massive, high-WTP (willingness to pay) pain point for B2B startups. \n* *Startup Idea*: An AI SaaS that ingests a founder's last 50 Gong/Zoom sales calls, extracts the exact objection-handling frameworks, identifies the specific conversational turns that trigger "aha" moments, and generates an interactive, voice-based AI roleplay simulator. New AEs practice pitching against this "AI Buyer" (which mimics real past prospects) until their simulation win rate matches the founder's—effectively productizing the founder's sales brain at scale."""},

