    {"q_id": "q5", "variant": "control", "prompt": "Our churn rate just spiked to 8% this month. What are the first three immediate actions I should take to diagnose and fix this?", "response": """Here are the first three immediate actions you should take to diagnose and fix a sudden spike in churn rate to 8%:\n\n1. **Segment the Churn Data (Find the "Who"):** Dive into your analytics to see if the churn is concentrated in a specific group. Segment the churned users by pricing tier, customer cohort (e.g., users who joined exactly 3 months ago), acquisition channel, geography, or company size. Identifying *who* is leaving will help pinpoint whether this is a broad product issue or localized to a specific segment.\n\n2. **Conduct Direct Outreach (Find the "Why"):** Immediately reach out to the customers who just canceled. Don't just rely on standard automated exit surveys—send a personalized, non-salesy email from a founder, PM, or CS lead asking for a quick, honest reply about why they left. Direct qualitative feedback is the fastest way to uncover the actual root cause (e.g., missing features, pricing, poor support).\n\n3. **Audit Recent Changes and System Health (Find the "Trigger"):** Investigate what changed internally or externally right before the spike. \n- **Internal:** Check for recent product bugs, downtime, UI/UX updates, or pricing changes.\n- **Billing:** Check your payment gateway for a spike in failed payments (involuntary churn).\n- **External:** Look at support ticket trends to see if there was a sudden surge in a specific type of complaint, or check if a competitor recently launched a major campaign."""},
    {"q_id": "q5", "variant": "fable_compressed", "prompt": "Our churn rate just spiked to 8% this month. What are the first three immediate actions I should take to diagnose and fix this?", "response": """A sudden spike to an 8% churn rate can be stressful, but taking a systematic approach will help you understand the root cause and stabilize the situation. Here are the first three immediate actions you should take:\n\n1. **Segment and Analyze the Churned Customers (Quantitative Analysis)**\n   * Look for common patterns among the users who left. Did they belong to a specific cohort, pricing tier, or industry? \n   * Check their usage data leading up to the cancellation. Did they experience recent bugs, service outages, or a sudden drop in engagement? Identifying these trends will help you pinpoint whether the issue is product-related, market-driven, or specific to a certain user group.\n\n2. **Reach Out for Direct Feedback (Qualitative Analysis)**\n   * Set up immediate, personalized outreach to the customers who just churned. A short, empathetic email from a founder or customer success leader asking "What could we have done better?" often yields honest, actionable insights.\n   * Review any recent support tickets, exit survey responses, or cancellation notes to see if customers are already telling you exactly why they are leaving (e.g., missing features, pricing sensitivity, competitor offers).\n\n3. **Identify and Secure At-Risk Accounts (Proactive Retention)**\n   * Use the patterns you found in step 1 to identify current active users who exhibit the same "pre-churn" behaviors (like declining login frequency or unused core features).\n   * Proactively engage these at-risk accounts with targeted check-ins, offers for additional training, or temporary discounts to stabilize your user base while you fix the underlying issues causing the churn spike."""},
